The interested reader is directed to a plethora of resources online, including ‚ÄúThe Rust Programming Language‚Äù ( https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/book/ ).

Background on Rust and its use in R Rust (https://www.rust-lang.org/ ) is a statically-typed, general-purpose programming lang uage which emphasizes memory safety without compromising runti me performance.

Rust Ô¨Årst appeared in 2010 as a Mozilla project, had its Ô¨Årst s table release in 2015, and has been rated the ‚Äúmost loved programming language‚Äù in the Stack Ove rÔ¨Çow Annual Developer Survey (https://insights.stackoverflow.com/survey/ ) every year since 2016.
The Ô¨Årst major effort to integrate R and Rust appears to have started in early 2016 with the now-d eprecated https://github.com/rustr project.
Another exciting project that interfaces R and Rust is the ex tendr project ( https://github.com/extendr ).
For example, on Windows, install Rtools ( https://cran.r-project.org/bin/windows/Rtools/ ).
On MacOS, follow the instructions here: https://mac.r-project.org/tools/ .
Next, install the Rust toolchain; the recommended way is rustup ( https://rustup.rs ).

One must download rustup-init.exe from https://rustup.rs , execute ‚Äò rustup-init.exe -y --default-host x86_64-pc-windows-gn u‚Äô, and then (in a new terminal so the changes to the PATH are picke d up), execute ‚Äò rustup target add i686-pc-windows-gnu ‚Äô.
The minimum required Cargo version should be updated and t he developer can determine this using cargo-msrv ( https://crates.io/crates/cargo-msrv ).

These are automati- cally generated by the bindgen utility ( https://rust-lang.github.io/rust-bindgen/ ) from the fol- lowing R header Ô¨Åles: ‚Äò Rversion.h ‚Äô, ‚ÄòR.h‚Äô, ‚ÄòRinternals.h ‚Äô, ‚ÄòRinterface.h ‚Äô, ‚ÄòR_ext/Rdynload.h ‚Äô, and ‚Äò Rmath.h ‚Äô, although only those deÔ¨Ånitions and functions that are docum ented to be part of R‚Äôs API (as speciÔ¨Åc by ‚ÄúWriting R Extensions‚Äù) should be used.

Rust and C themselves are not benchmarked here, but the reader is referred to The Compu ter Language Benchmarks Game (https://benchmarksgame-team.pages.debian.net/benchm arksgame/ ), which shows Rust beating GCC‚Äôs C in about half of the benchmarks.
